Part 1: Order Life Cycle Documentation
1. Architecture & Core Interfaces
Before diving into the process flow, it is important to understand the underlying tool architecture that manages connections to AWS SQS.
ToolFactory (Interface): Manages the lifecycle of a tool. It mandates three core methods:
init(): Prepares the environment.
getInstance(): Retrieves the active instance/connection.
destroy(): Cleans up resources.
SQSToolFactory (Implementation): Implements ToolFactory<V> specifically for AWS SQS.
init(): Connects to AWS and initializes the cache, preparing a place to store connections for reuse.
getInstance(): Establishes and returns the actual SQS connection.
destroy(): Terminates the tool support and closes connections when the application ends.
SQSTool (Class): Provides the specific operations for interacting with SQS. Key methods include:
getClient(): Returns the SQS client.
getQueueUrl(): Retrieves the endpoint URL.
receiveMessage(): Requests messages from the SQS client.
deleteMessage(): Removes a single message from the queue.
deleteMessageBatch(): Removes multiple messages from the queue efficiently.
canConnect(): Verifies if the SQS client is connected.
2. The Execution Flow: Processing SQS Orders
Phase A: Ingestion (ConsumeSqsOrderMessage)
Initialization: The process begins by initializing the SQSTool (passing the tool name, SQS.class, and SystemMessageRemoteId).
Fetch Messages: It calls sqsTool.receiveMessage(), requesting a batch of messages (maximum of 10) using the SQSClient and endpoint URL.
Parse & Map Data:
The raw messages are converted into JSON format (bodyMap).
The system extracts the X-Shopify-Shop-Domain from the message metadata.
It queries the database to find the corresponding SystemMessageRemoteId (smrId) for that specific Shopify domain.
It extracts the OrderId from the JSON payload.
Group Orders: The system organizes the orders into a Map called orderIdsByRemotes, structured as [smrId : List<OrderId>].

Phase B: Staging Data (stage#ShopifyOrder) 
5. Iterate & Call: The system iterates over the orderIdsByRemotes map. For each smrId, it calls the stage#ShopifyOrder service, passing three fields: orderIdList, systemMessageRemoteId, and _jobRunId. 

6. Fetch Order Details: Inside the staging service, it loops through the orderIdList and calls get#ShopifyOrderDetails for each order. * Inputs passed: smrId, shopifyOrderId 
7. GraphQL Requests (Send#ShopifyGraphql): * The get#ShopifyOrderDetails service generates GraphQL queryText. * It makes a service call to Send#ShopifyGraphql to get the Order Header. 
Phase C: Aggregation & Cleanup 
8. Upload to MDM: Once all unified order details are fetched, the stage#ShopifyOrder service aggregates the JSON data into a file. It then calls uploadDataManagerFile to push this file to the Master Data Management (MDM) system. 
9. Queue Cleanup: Finally, control returns to SqsConsumeOrder. For all the messages that were successfully processed and staged, it calls sqsTool.deleteMessageBatch() to remove them from the AWS SQS queue.

